Git Beginner-to-Working Cheat Sheet (Practical DevOps Style)
Git is basically your time machine + collaboration system for code and infrastructure.

As a Cloud/DevOps/SRE engineer, Git becomes part of daily life:

Terraform code

Kubernetes YAMLs

Python scripts

CI/CD pipelines

Helm charts

Documentation

Automation scripts

You don’t need to memorize everything. Learn the workflow.

1. Install Git
Verify Git Installation
git --version
Example:

git version 2.49.0
2. First-Time Git Configuration
This sets your identity globally.

Configure Username
git config --global user.name "Aryan Singh"
Configure Email
git config --global user.email "aryan@example.com"
Verify Configuration
git config --list
3. Create Your First Git Project
Create Folder
mkdir myproject
cd myproject
4. Initialize Git Repository
This creates .git hidden directory.

git init
Output:

Initialized empty Git repository
5. Check Git Status
MOST USED COMMAND.

git status
Shows:

modified files

new files

staged files

branch info

6. Create Files
Example:

touch app.py
touch README.md
Or:

echo "Hello Git" > README.md
7. Add Files to Staging Area
Add Single File
git add app.py
Add All Files
git add .
Think:

Working directory → Staging area → Commit

8. Commit Changes
Save snapshot/version.

git commit -m "Initial commit"
Example:

git commit -m "Added terraform networking module"
9. View Commit History
git log
Short format:

git log --oneline
10. Branch Basics
Branch = separate workspace.

Main branch:

main
Older systems:

master
11. Check Current Branch
git branch
Current branch has *

Example:

* main
12. Create New Branch
Create Branch
git branch dev
13. Switch Branch
git checkout dev
Modern way:

git switch dev
14. Create + Switch Branch Together
MOST USED.

git checkout -b feature-login
Modern:

git switch -c feature-login
15. Merge Branch
Go to main branch:

git checkout main
Merge:

git merge feature-login
16. Delete Branch
git branch -d feature-login
Force delete:

git branch -D feature-login
17. Connect GitHub Repository
Create repo on GitHub

Then connect local repo:

git remote add origin https://github.com/username/myproject.git
Verify:

git remote -v
18. Push Code to GitHub
First push:

git push -u origin main
Later:

git push
19. Clone Existing Repository
MOST COMMON IN COMPANIES.

git clone https://github.com/username/project.git
Example:

git clone https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes.git
This downloads complete repo.

20. Pull Latest Changes
Get latest code from remote.

git pull
Specific:

git pull origin main
21. Fetch Changes
Downloads changes WITHOUT merging.

git fetch
Good for checking updates safely.

22. Check Differences
Before Staging
git diff
After Staging
git diff --staged
23. Undo Changes
Undo Unstaged Changes
git checkout -- app.py
Modern:

git restore app.py
24. Remove File from Staging
git restore --staged app.py
25. Rename Branch
git branch -m oldname newname
26. Remove Files
git rm test.txt
Commit after removing:

git commit -m "Removed unused file"
27. Ignore Files (.gitignore)
Create:

touch .gitignore
Example:

*.log
*.tmp
.env
__pycache__/
terraform.tfstate
VERY IMPORTANT in DevOps.

Never commit:

passwords

secrets

tokens

private keys

tfstate with secrets

28. Stash Changes (Temporary Save)
Useful when switching tasks.

Save:

git stash
Restore:

git stash pop
Check stash:

git stash list
29. Reset Commits
Soft Reset
Keep files:

git reset --soft HEAD~1
Hard Reset
DANGER:

git reset --hard HEAD~1
Deletes changes permanently.

30. See Remote Repository
git remote -v
31. Tags (Versioning)
git tag v1.0
Push tags:

git push origin v1.0
Used in:

releases

CI/CD

deployments

32. Fork vs Clone
Fork
Copy someone else's repo into YOUR GitHub account.

Used for:

open-source contribution

Done on GitHub UI.

Clone
Download repo locally.

git clone <repo-url>
33. Real Corporate Workflow
Typical DevOps flow:

git clone repo
git checkout -b feature/terraform-network
