Configure Your GitHub Account with Git (Complete Beginner Setup)
This is the setup every engineer does after installing Git.

Goal:

Your Laptop ↔ Git ↔ GitHub
You need:

Git installed

GitHub account

Authentication setup

STEP 1 — Create GitHub Account
Go to:

GitHub Official Website

Create account if not already created.

STEP 2 — Configure Git Identity
This tells Git who you are.

Set Username
git config --global user.name "Aryan Singh"
Set Email
Use SAME email as GitHub account.

git config --global user.email "your-email@gmail.com"
STEP 3 — Verify Configuration
git config --list
You should see:

user.name=Aryan Singh
user.email=your-email@gmail.com
STEP 4 — Generate SSH Key (BEST METHOD)
GitHub no longer likes password authentication for Git operations.

Use SSH keys.

Check Existing SSH Keys
Linux:

ls -al ~/.ssh
Windows Git Bash:

ls -al /c/Users/YOUR_USERNAME/.ssh
If no keys exist, generate one.

STEP 5 — Generate New SSH Key
Recommended:

ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your-email@gmail.com"
Older systems:

ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -C "your-email@gmail.com"
STEP 6 — Press Enter Through Prompts
Example:

Enter file in which to save the key:
/home/aryan/.ssh/id_ed25519
Press ENTER.

Optional passphrase:

Enter passphrase:
You can:

set passphrase (more secure)

or press Enter

STEP 7 — Start SSH Agent
Linux/macOS:

eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"
STEP 8 — Add SSH Key
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
STEP 9 — Copy Public SSH Key
Linux:

cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub
Windows Git Bash:

cat /c/Users/YOUR_USERNAME/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub
Copy COMPLETE output.

Looks like:

ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAI.... your-email@gmail.com
STEP 10 — Add SSH Key to GitHub
Go to:

GitHub SSH Settings

Then:

Click "New SSH Key"

Give title:

My Laptop
Paste copied key

Save

STEP 11 — Test Connection
ssh -T git@github.com
Expected:

Hi username! You've successfully authenticated.
Done. Your laptop now trusts GitHub.

STEP 12 — Clone Repository Using SSH
Instead of HTTPS:

https://github.com/user/repo.git
Use SSH:

git@github.com:user/repo.git
Example:

git clone git@github.com:aryan/myproject.git
STEP 13 — Push Your First Code
Create Folder
mkdir demo
cd demo
Initialize Git
git init
Create File
echo "Hello GitHub" > README.md
Add File
git add .
Commit
git commit -m "Initial commit"
STEP 14 — Create Repository on GitHub
Go to:

Create New GitHub Repository

Create:

demo
DO NOT:

initialize README

add gitignore

add license

Because local repo already exists.

STEP 15 — Connect Local Repo to GitHub
Copy SSH URL from GitHub.

Example:

git remote add origin git@github.com:aryan/demo.git
Verify:

git remote -v
STEP 16 — Push Code
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main
Done.

Your code is now on GitHub.

HTTPS METHOD (Alternative)
If SSH feels difficult initially.

Clone Using HTTPS
git clone https://github.com/user/repo.git
During push:
GitHub asks authentication.

Now GitHub uses:

Personal Access Token (PAT)
NOT passwords.

Create GitHub Personal Access Token
Go to:

GitHub Tokens Settings

Generate token:

repo access

expiration

Use token as password.

Recommended for DevOps Engineers
Use:

SSH Authentication
Because:

cleaner

secure

automation friendly

CI/CD compatible

no repeated login

